<p>Bazı pırlantalar UV ışık altında mavi floresan gösterir. Güçlü floresan, J-K rengindeki taşları gün ışığında daha beyaz gösterebilir — bir avantaj. Ancak D-F renklerde güçlü floresan nadiren "yağlı" bir görünüm yaratabilir. Orta floresan genellikle zararsızdır ve fiyat indirimi sağlar.</p>
<h3>Kaynak Notu</h3>
<p>GIA renk derecelendirme sistemi ve King vd. (2008) "Color Grading of Colored Diamonds" çalışmasına dayanmaktadır.</p>`,
  en: `<h2>Color — The D-to-Z Diamond Color Scale</h2>
<p>In diamonds, color paradoxically measures colorlessness. The GIA scale runs from D (completely colorless) to Z (light yellow or brown tint). D-F is "colorless," G-J "near colorless," K-M "faint," and N-Z "very light."</p>
<h3>Why Start at D?</h3>
<p>GIA deliberately chose D in 1953 to break from earlier inconsistent A-B-C systems, preventing confusion between old and new grading.</p>
<h3>Perceiving Color Differences</h3>
<p>D-E-F differences are only distinguishable under controlled lighting with a white background and side-by-side comparison. A G-color diamond set in a ring appears colorless to most observers. G-H-I grades are nicknamed "hidden colorless" and offer excellent value.</p>
<h3>Fancy Color Diamonds</h3>
<p>Beyond Z, intensely colored diamonds enter the "fancy color" category with a reversed valuation: deeper saturation means greater value. Fancy Vivid Yellow, Fancy Intense Pink, and Fancy Deep Blue are extremely rare and valuable. The famous Hope Diamond is fancy deep grayish blue.</p>
<h3>Metal and Color Interaction</h3>
<p>Yellow or rose gold can mask the warmth of K-L colors, while white gold or platinum best showcases D-H stones. Always consider setting choice alongside color grade.</p>
<h3>Source Note</h3>
<p>Based on GIA color grading system and King et al. (2008) "Color Grading of Colored Diamonds."</p>`,
